You’re circling a good question: what exactly is intuition?
The phrases you mentioned (“smells fishy,” “gut feeling,” “rings true,” “something’s off”) are clues about how people experience it.

Let’s build a grounded definition from those.

⸻

1. What those phrases reveal

Across languages, intuition is often described using sensory metaphors:

Phrase	Sense referenced	What it implies
“smells fishy”	smell	detecting something wrong before knowing why
“gut feeling”	internal sensation	body-level signal
“rings true”	hearing	pattern alignment
“see what you mean”	vision	sudden recognition

These metaphors exist because intuition feels like a perception rather than a thought.

⸻

2. A working definition

A good scientific-style definition might be:

intuition = rapid, unconscious pattern recognition
that produces a feeling of knowing
before explicit reasoning occurs

Or even more compact:

intuition = compressed experience returning as a signal

Your brain has seen patterns before. It compares current signals to past ones and fires a prediction signal.

You experience that as a feeling.

⸻

3. Why intuition feels mysterious

Most cognitive processing happens below conscious awareness.

The brain is constantly doing something like this:

environment signals
↓
pattern matching with past experience
↓
prediction of outcomes
↓
feeling signal (good / bad / uncertain)

The reasoning chain is hidden, so you only feel the output signal.

That’s intuition.

⸻

4. Why scent metaphors appear

Smell is one of the oldest sensory systems in evolution.

Animals use scent for:
	•	danger detection
	•	food identification
	•	social signaling
	•	environmental awareness

Because smell works fast and unconsciously, it became a natural metaphor for intuition.

So when people say:

“Something smells wrong”

they’re describing a low-level pattern detector firing.

⸻

5. The “gut feeling” is partly literal

There actually is a biological reason people talk about the gut.

Humans have a huge neural network in the digestive system called the enteric nervous system.

It contains hundreds of millions of neurons and communicates with the brain through the vagus nerve.

The gut also produces neurotransmitters like serotonin.

So emotional signals and stress responses can genuinely be felt in the abdomen.

⸻

6. Pheromones and unconscious signals

Humans don’t use pheromones the way ants or insects do, but we do respond to subtle chemical and behavioral cues:
	•	body odor changes with emotional state
	•	facial microexpressions
	•	posture and tone
	•	stress hormones detectable in scent

Your brain picks up many of these signals without conscious awareness.

That contributes to intuitive impressions about people.

⸻

7. When intuition works best

Intuition tends to be reliable in environments where someone has lots of experience.

Examples:
	•	firefighters sensing structural collapse
	•	chess players recognizing board patterns
	•	doctors recognizing symptoms quickly

In these cases, intuition is really high-speed expertise.

⸻

8. When intuition fails

Intuition can also misfire when:
	•	situations are unfamiliar
	•	biases are strong
	•	emotional stress is high

Because the pattern matcher may be using the wrong reference patterns.

⸻

9. The “geode” you mentioned

Your geode metaphor fits nicely.

Intuition is like:

experience crystals
compressed inside the brain

When the right stimulus hits them, the pattern structure lights up instantly.

The reasoning layers are there, but hidden.

⸻

10. A clean definition you could keep

If we compress everything:

Intuition:
the brain’s fast pattern-detection system
that converts accumulated experience
into a feeling signal guiding attention and decisions.


